
* LOGIT: : Model Fit

* Reference Model Sample Size
logit vote c.lmv_re i.labcon2 i.class5 i.cat_skill c.rlgdgr i.gender i.ethnie2 c.age  ///
    c.agea c.nat_unemp c.gdp i.cntry_num i.essround [pweight=newweight2], vce(cluster cntry_num)
	

* STATUS-BASED 
	
logit vote i.labcon2 i.class5 i.cat_skill c.rlgdgr i.gender ///
      i.ethnie2 c.age c.agea c.nat_unemp c.gdp i.cntry_num i.essround if e(sample), ///
      vce(cluster cntry_num)
estimates store M_full

logit vote i.labcon2 c.EPL_R i.class5 i.cat_skill c.rlgdgr i.gender ///
      i.ethnie2 c.age c.agea c.nat_unemp c.gdp i.cntry_num i.essround if e(sample), ///
      vce(cluster cntry_num)
estimates store M_epl

logit vote i.labcon2##c.EPL_R i.class5 i.cat_skill c.rlgdgr i.gender ///
      i.ethnie2 c.age c.agea c.nat_unemp c.gdp i.cntry_num i.essround if e(sample), ///
      vce(cluster cntry_num)
estimates store M_inter

estimates stats M_full M_epl M_inter     //  AIC/BIC 

/*
Basic logistic diagnostics (residuals, leverage, and DFBETAs) do not indicate any undue influence of individual observations, and re-estimating the models while dropping single countries leaves the main results unchanged, suggesting that the findings are not driven by outliers or single country leverage.
*/

logit vote i.labcon2##c.EPL_R i.class5 i.cat_skill c.rlgdgr i.gender ///
      i.ethnie2 c.age c.agea c.nat_unemp c.gdp i.cntry_num i.essround if e(sample), ///
      vce(cluster cntry_num)
estimates store M_inter

estat gof, group(10)                     // Hosmer-Lemeshow
lroc                                     // ROC mit AUC

/*
To assess the final model's model fit, I first conducted a Hosmer Lemeshow goodness of fit test using ten quantiles of the predicted probabilities. The test yields Chi-X(8) = 9.98 with a p-value of 0.266, providing no evidence against the null hypothesis of adequate fit. The model does not display systematic deviations between observed and predicted values. I then examined the model's discriminative performance using the ROC curve. The area under the curve, >AUC<, is 0.765, indicating a very solid ability to distinguish between voters and non-voters.
*/

* Wald-Test

logit vote i.labcon2 c.EPL_R i.class5 i.cat_skill c.rlgdgr i.gender ///
      i.ethnie2 c.age c.agea c.nat_unemp c.gdp i.cntry_num i.essround if e(sample), ///
      vce(cluster cntry_num)

test EPL_R  


logit vote i.labcon2##c.EPL_R i.class5 i.cat_skill c.rlgdgr i.gender ///
      i.ethnie2 c.age c.agea c.nat_unemp c.gdp i.cntry_num i.essround if e(sample), ///
      vce(cluster cntry_num)

test 1.labcon2#c.EPL_R

test EPL_R 1.labcon2#c.EPL_R

/*
While the overall coefficient for EPL was not statistically significant, the marginal effect on the probability of voting showed a significant effect for status-based labor market dualization. This suggests 
that the relationship between EPL and voting behavior is conditional on contract type.
*/


logit vote i.labcon2##c.EPL_R i.class5 i.cat_skill c.rlgdgr i.gender ///
      i.ethnie2 c.age c.agea c.nat_unemp c.gdp i.cntry_num i.essround if e(sample), ///
      vce(cluster cntry_num)
      
estat classification 

/*
The classification table reveals that the model correctly classifies 84.5% of all cases. The model demonstrates high sensitivity (98.4%), correctly identifying nearly all voters, but low specificity (10.9%), meaning it  struggles to identify non-voters. This pattern is typical for models with 
unbalanced dependent variables, where 84% of respondents reported voting.  The positive predictive value of 85.4% indicates that when the model predicts  voting, it is correct in the majority of cases.
*/



/*
Three nested logistic regression models were estimated with clustered standard errors. Model comparisons show nearly identical fit across specifications (Pseudo R â‰ˆ 0.144), with Wald tests indicating that adding EPL does not significantly improve model fit (p = 0.992 for main effect; p = 0.288 for interaction). The final model demonstrates good fit. Hosmer-Lemeshow test Chi X (8) = 9.98, p = 0.266; AUC = 0.765 84.5% correctly classified. Robustness checks confirm stable results. While overall EPL coefficients are not statistically significant, marginal effects analysis suggests a conditional relationship between EPL and voting behavior depending on contract type.
*/
